[[Category:1928 in biology]]

An '''infrared excess''' is a measurement of an astronomical source, typically a [[star]], that in their [[spectral energy distribution]] has a greater measured [[infrared]] [[radiative flux|flux]] than expected by assuming the star is a [[blackbody radiation|blackbody radiator]].  Infrared excesses are often the result of [[circumstellar dust]] and are common in [[young stellar object]]s and evolved stars on the [[asymptotic giant branch]] or [[Post-AGB|older]].

In addition, monitoring for infrared excess emission from stellar systems is one possible method that could enable a search for large-scale stellar engineering projects of a hypothetical extraterrestrial civilization; for example a [[Dyson sphere]] or [[Dyson swarm]].<ref>http://m.space.com/24269-how-to-search-for-alien-civilizations.html</ref>

